Hubble Uses Moon As “Mirror” to Study Earth’s Atmosphere – Proxy in Search of Potentially Habitable Planets Around Other Stars </h1><div class="entry-tags clearfix"><span>TOPICS:</span><a href="https://scitechdaily.com/tag/astronomy/" rel="tag">Astronomy</a><a href="https://scitechdaily.com/tag/european-space-agency/" rel="tag">European Space Agency</a><a href="https://scitechdaily.com/tag/exoplanet/" rel="tag">Exoplanet</a><a href="https://scitechdaily.com/tag/hubble-space-telescope/" rel="tag">Hubble Space Telescope</a><a href="https://scitechdaily.com/tag/moon/" rel="tag">Moon</a><a href="https://scitechdaily.com/tag/nasa/" rel="tag">NASA</a><a href="https://scitechdaily.com/tag/popular/" rel="tag">Popular</a></div> </header><p class="entry-meta">
<span class="entry-by">By</span> <span class="entry-meta-author vcard author">ESA/Hubble</span>
<span class="entry-meta-date updated">August 6, 2020</span>
</p>
<div class="entry-content clearfix">
<div id="attachment_91690" style="width: 787px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><a href="https://scitechdaily.com/images/Hubble-Observes-the-Total-Lunar-Eclipse.jpg"><img aria-describedby="caption-attachment-91690" loading="lazy" class="size-large wp-image-91690" src="https://scitechdaily.com/images/Hubble-Observes-the-Total-Lunar-Eclipse-777x433.jpg" alt="Hubble Observes the Total Lunar Eclipse" width="777" height="433" srcset="https://scitechdaily.com/images/Hubble-Observes-the-Total-Lunar-Eclipse-777x433.jpg 777w, https://scitechdaily.com/images/Hubble-Observes-the-Total-Lunar-Eclipse-400x223.jpg 400w, https://scitechdaily.com/images/Hubble-Observes-the-Total-Lunar-Eclipse-768x428.jpg 768w, https://scitechdaily.com/images/Hubble-Observes-the-Total-Lunar-Eclipse-180x101.jpg 180w, https://scitechdaily.com/images/Hubble-Observes-the-Total-Lunar-Eclipse-260x146.jpg 260w, https://scitechdaily.com/images/Hubble-Observes-the-Total-Lunar-Eclipse-120x67.jpg 120w, https://scitechdaily.com/images/Hubble-Observes-the-Total-Lunar-Eclipse.jpg 1410w" sizes="(max-width: 777px) 100vw, 777px" /></a><p id="caption-attachment-91690" class="wp-caption-text">Taking advantage of a total lunar eclipse in January 2019, astronomers using NASA&rsquo;s Hubble Space Telescope have detected ozone in Earth&rsquo;s atmosphere. This method serves as a proxy for how they will observe Earth-like planets transiting in front of other stars in search of life. Our planet&rsquo;s perfect alignment with the Sun and Moon during a total lunar eclipse mimics the geometry of a transiting terrestrial planet with its star. In a new study, Hubble did not look at Earth directly. Instead, astronomers used the Moon as a mirror that reflects the sunlight transmitted through Earth&rsquo;s atmosphere, which was then captured by Hubble. This is the first time a total lunar eclipse was captured at ultraviolet wavelengths and from a space telescope. Credit: M. Kornmesser (ESA/Hubble), NASA, and ESA</p></div>
<h3>Hubble Uses Our Moon to Probe Earth&rsquo;s Atmosphere During a Lunar Eclipse</h3>
<p>Astronauts who have gazed at Earth from space have been awestruck at our blue marble planet&rsquo;s majesty and diversity. Mike Massimino, who helped service the <span aria-describedby="tt" class="glossaryLink" data-cmtooltip="&lt;div class=glossaryItemTitle&gt;Hubble Space Telescope&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class=glossaryItemBody&gt;The Hubble Space Telescope (often referred to as Hubble or HST) is one of NASA's Great Observatories and was launched into low Earth orbit in 1990. It is one of the largest and most versatile space telescopes in use and features a 2.4-meter mirror and four main instruments that observe in the ultraviolet, visible, and near-infrared regions of the electromagnetic spectrum. It was named after astronomer Edwin Hubble.&lt;/div&gt;">Hubble Space Telescope</span> in orbit, said, &ldquo;I think of our planet as a paradise. We are very lucky to be here.&rdquo;</p>
<p>What&rsquo;s mind-blowing is that astronomers estimate there could be as many as 1 billion other planets like Earth in our <span aria-describedby="tt" class="glossaryLink" data-cmtooltip="&lt;div class=glossaryItemTitle&gt;Milky Way&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class=glossaryItemBody&gt;The Milky Way is the galaxy that contains the Earth, and is named for its appearance from Earth. It is a barred spiral galaxy that contains an estimated 100-400 billion stars and has a diameter between 150,000 and 200,000 light-years.&lt;/div&gt;">Milky Way</span> galaxy alone. Just imagine, one billion &ndash; not million &ndash; other &ldquo;paradise planets.&rdquo; But it&rsquo;s paradise lost if nothing is living there to marvel at sunsets in azure blue skies. And, as 19th century philosopher Thomas Carlyle mused, &ldquo;&hellip;what a waste of space.&rdquo;</p>
<p>It is sobering that our home planet is the only known place in the universe where life as we know it exists and thrives. And so, we gaze outward to the stars, imprisoned by space and time, into a cosmic loneliness. That&rsquo;s why scientists are dedicated to building ever-larger telescopes to search for potentially habitable planets. But how will they know life is present without traveling there and watching creatures walk, fly, or slither around?</p>
